Format is sufficient for now. I would not freeze it into files until you make five changes.

**Key fixes**
- The `independent integrity panel` cannot be the final legal decision-maker. Under the Procurement Act 2023, the contracting authority must identify, keep under review, mitigate, and record conflicts. Make the panel an assurance/clearance body, but keep final ownership with DSIT or whoever is the contracting authority. Source: [GOV.UK conflicts guidance, updated 9 March 2026](https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/procurement-act-2023-guidance-documents-define-phase/guidance-conflicts-of-interest-html), [Procurement Act notes on sections 81-83](https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2023/54/notes/division/6/index.htm).
- The `non-QSL evaluation route` should be discretionary, not automatic. Official guidance says the authority may require the supplier to take reasonable mitigation steps; if unfair advantage cannot be avoided, exclusion can follow. Do not give vendors a guaranteed route-switch by hiring a QSL person late. That is a gaming hole. Source: [GOV.UK conflicts guidance](https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/procurement-act-2023-guidance-documents-define-phase/guidance-conflicts-of-interest-html).
- The `publication` promises are too aggressive. The Act requires confirmation that a conflicts assessment has been prepared and reviewed; it does not require publishing the assessment itself or named personnel. Use auditor attestation or role-based disclosure, not named clean-team rosters to vendors. Source: [GOV.UK conflicts guidance](https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/procurement-act-2023-guidance-documents-define-phase/guidance-conflicts-of-interest-html).
- The `6- and 12-month cooling-off periods` read arbitrary. Tie them to the procurement lifecycle: pre-tender involvement, evaluation, award, challenge/standstill, and any material contract-change decision touching the same subsystem. If you keep fixed months, label them as policy choices, not legal necessities.
- The `materiality` table should use rebuttable presumptions, not hard safe-harbour thresholds. A `>£5k` rule will be gamed, and low-value relationships can still matter if they create vendor-specific insight or influence.

**Framing**
- Lead with procurement integrity, not subsidy control. The strongest legal frame is section 12(1)(d) plus sections 81-83: actual, potential, and perceived conflicts; people who can influence decisions; and unfair supplier advantage. Source: [GOV.UK conflicts guidance](https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/procurement-act-2023-guidance-documents-define-phase/guidance-conflicts-of-interest-html).
- I would soften the legal claim from “blanket exclusion fails” to: this is a blunt instrument, and DSIT should explain why narrower mitigations are not a reasonable way to protect integrity. That is an inference from the guidance, and it is safer than asserting a legal entitlement.
- Best one-line DSIT formulation: `The relevant control surface is decision influence and unfair supplier advantage, not employer label.`

**Practical recommendation**
- Don’t retry file writes yet.
- Fold in the legal corrections above, then persist the draft.
- If DSIT wants a Phase 1 simplifier, the clean fallback is: `Permitted` class only, with Restricted-class cases deferred unless the contracting authority is satisfied the mitigation is auditable and the supplier gains no unfair advantage.

