This is now close to freeze. The core frame is aligned with the Act: the real test is who can influence procurement decisions, not who employs them. That matches [section 81(3)](https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2023/54/pdfs/ukpga_20230054_en.pdf?view=interweave+extent) and the current [Cabinet Office conflicts guidance, updated 9 March 2026](https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/procurement-act-2023-guidance-documents-define-phase/guidance-conflicts-of-interest-html).

I would make three final edits before persisting:
- In §1, fix the legal hook. `Section 12(1)(d)` is the integrity objective; the unfair-advantage language sits more cleanly in `section 12(3)`, and prior-involvement risk is most directly addressed by `section 16`. Keep `sections 81–83` for conflict identification, mitigation, and assessment.
- In §3, add that if the contracting authority departs from the integrity panel’s recommendation, it must give written reasons and record them in the conflicts assessment/register. Otherwise the panel looks advisory in a weak, cosmetic sense.
- In §5, make the backstop explicit: mitigate first, route-switch if appropriate, and if unfair advantage still cannot be avoided, the supplier must be excluded from that procurement. That is the mandatory result under [section 82](https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2023/54/pdfs/ukpga_20230054_en.pdf?view=interweave+extent) and is echoed for prior involvement in [section 16 / explanatory notes](https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2023/54/notes/division/6/index.htm).

One optional wording tweak: in §4, I would soften “methodology published” to “fixed, version-controlled, and lodged with the contracting authority before bids; disclosed to suppliers only to the extent required by the procurement design.” That part is an inference, but it avoids overcommitting to publication.

